Question

A wallpaper was made by using repeated translations. I have depicted the translation of point \((0.15, -0.51)\) in the direction \(\theta=1.28\) (radians) by a distance of \(r=2.1\).


What are the coordinates of the point at the end of the arrow (the result of the translation)?

  • The horizontal coordinate, \(x'=\) ##ANSWER1##
  • The vertical coordinate, \(y'=\) ##ANSWER2##

Answerlist

  • 0.66
  • 0.69
  • 0.72
  • 0.75
  • 0.78
  • 1.38
  • 1.41
  • 1.44
  • 1.47
  • 1.5

Solution

To find the changes of translation, we can use trigonometry.

\[\Delta x = r\cdot \cos(\theta)\] \[\Delta y = r\cdot \sin(\theta)\]

Let’s evaluate those changes.

\[\Delta x ~=~ 2.1\cdot \cos(1.28) ~=~ 0.6\] \[\Delta y ~=~ 2.1\cdot \sin(1.28) ~=~ 2.01\]

We can then add these changes to the original point.

\[x' ~=~ x+\Delta x ~=~0.15+0.6 ~=~ 0.75\] \[y' ~=~ y+\Delta y ~=~ -0.51+2.01 ~=~ 1.5\]
